# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1998-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The **1878 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1878, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the third season of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1877, two teams would fold: Brooklyn Hartfords and St.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] They were replaced by the Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Later in the offseason, the Providence Grays would join on February 6, raising the number of teams to seven.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] On April 1 or 2, the Louisville Grays would officially resign from the league, once again lowering the number of teams to six.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The 1878 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] This format had been in place since the previous season, and would be the final season which saw this format, due to expansion to eight teams the following season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all six teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Indianapolis Blues and Providence Grays.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Four tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues had three tie games.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Milwaukee Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave the 23rd Street Grounds (where they played for four seasons since their National Association days from 1874) and move to Lakefront Park where they would play for seven seasons through 1884.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The **1879 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1879, and saw the Providence Grays as the pennant winner of the fourth season of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League was set on expanding from a six-team league to an eight-team league.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays folded, and in its place, the league admitted the Cleveland Blues, the International Association's Buffalo Bisons and Syracuse Stars, and finally (with confirmation Milwaukee was not returning) the Troy Trojans.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] It is suggested by Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) that this season featured the first African-American to play major league baseball, William Edward White, who played one game with the Providence Grays on June 21.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] He predates brothers Moses Fleetwood Walker and Weldy Walker by five years, and Jackie Robinson by 68 years.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The 1879 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 12-games-each format that had been in place since 1877, as the National League expanded from six to eight teams, adding 24 games to each team's schedule.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Five tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings had four tie games.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Reds, Providence Grays, and Syracuse Stars had one tie game each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at the Putnam Grounds on September 20 against the Chicago White Stockings, moving to Haymakers' Grounds for the start of the 1880 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The **1880 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 1, 1880, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the fifth season of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 season is known for the first two major league perfect games in history, as well as being the only perfect games in the 19th century.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Thrown by Lee Richmond and John Ward, these two perfect games were thrown in the span of five days, the shortest amount of time between two perfect games (the next closest is currently 20 days between Dallas Braden's May 9 and Roy Halladay's and May 29, 2010 perfect games).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] A perfect game would not be seen again in the Major Leagues for 24 years when Cy Young threw his perfect game in 1904.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the Cincinnati Reds and Syracuse Stars disbanded, and were replaced by the Cincinnati Stars and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the Stars' only major league season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1883.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 1, featuring a doubleheader between the Providence Grays and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Eight tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Stars, and Providence Grays had three tie games each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, and Worcester Worcesters had two tie games each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave the Putnam Grounds (where they played their inaugural seasons) and move to the Haymakers' Grounds, where they would play for two seasons through 1881.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans begin to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on September 11.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The **1881 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through September 30, 1881, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the sixth season of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 season is most known for featuring the first major league grand slam.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Roger Connor of the Troy Trojans hit the walk-off home run at Riverside Park (Greenbush) against the Worcester Worcesters on September 10, leading to an 8–7 victory.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League dropped the Cincinnati Stars because the team refused to sign a league pledge that banned alcohol in league parks and forbade clubs from renting their parks out on Sundays.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The team was replaced by the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] 1881 would be the final season of the first National League monopoly-era, as the American Association would be established in 1882.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1879 and would be used until 1883.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring four teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Two tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues, Providence Grays, Troy Trojans, and Worcester Worcesters had one tie game each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines join the National League and play at Recreation Park in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at Haymakers' Grounds on September 30 against the Detroit Wolverines, moving to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds for the start of the 1882 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on June 15 and September 10.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The **1998 Major League Baseball season** ended with the New York Yankees sweeping the San Diego Padres in the World Series, after they had won a then AL record 114 regular season games.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees finished with 125 wins for the season (regular season and playoffs combined), which remains the MLB record.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The 1998 season was marked by MLB's expansion to 30 teams (16 in the NL, 14 in the AL), with two new teams–the Arizona Diamondbacks in the National League, and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in the American League–added.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] To keep the leagues with even numbers of teams while allowing both leagues to have a new team, the Milwaukee Brewers were moved from the American League Central Division to the National League Central Division.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers were shifted from the American League East to the American League Central, while the Devil Rays were added to the American League East.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The Diamondbacks were added to the National League West, making the NL have more teams than the AL for the first time (this arrangement would last until the end of the 2012 season, when the Houston Astros moved from the National to the American League for 2013, giving each league 15 teams).
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The biggest story of the season was the historic chase of the single-season home run record held at the time by Roger Maris.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr. of the Seattle Mariners started the season on a pace to both break Maris' record.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] In June, the chase was joined by the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa, who broke the decades-old record of Rudy York for most home runs in a calendar month with 20 that month.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Eventually, Griffey fell off the record pace, but still ended with 56 homers.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Both McGwire and Sosa broke the record in September, with McGwire ultimately finishing with 70 homers to Sosa's 66.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] McGwire's record would last only three years, with Barry Bonds hitting 73 in 2001.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The 1998 season was also the first in MLB history with four players hitting 50 or more homers, with Greg Vaughn of the San Diego Padres hitting 50.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] In a postscript to the record chase, both McGwire and Sosa have since been widely accused of having used performance-enhancing drugs during that period, and McGwire would admit in 2010 that he had used steroids during the record-setting season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The defending World Series champions Florida Marlins finished last in the NL East Division at 54–108, making it the first, and only, time that a team went from winning the World Series one year to finishing with 100 or more losses and last in their division the following year.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] On July 9, 1998, Major League Baseball Executive Council chairman Bud Selig officially became the 9th commissioner of baseball, though he had been the de facto commissioner for nearly 6 years.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] During that time, the owners had tried to find a replacement for previous commissioner Fay Vincent who was forced to step down by the owners towards the end of 1992 season mainly due to the lockout he intervened in during the 1990 season.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season in which teams were seeded by their respective win–loss record within their respective leagues.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third season under the five-year rights agreements with ESPN, Fox, and NBC.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] ESPN continued to air *Sunday Night Baseball* and *Wednesday Night Baseball*.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Fox's coverage included *Fox Saturday Baseball* broadcasts, Thursday night games on Fox Sports Net, and Saturday primetime games on FX.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] During the postseason, ESPN, Fox, and NBC split the four Division Series.
[src:1998-major-league-baseball-season/1998-major-league-baseball-season] NBC then televised the American League Championship Series while Fox aired both the National League Championship Series and the World Series.
